07143nam a22007455i 9780773564299DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735642997 a10.1515/97807735642992doi  a(DE-B1597)654921  a(OCoLC)732601090  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1021.2bB43 1993eb 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a306/.09711 aFlaherty, David H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeaver Bites Back? /cFrank E. Manning, David H. Flaherty. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tContributors -- tAbbreviations -- tReversible Resistance: Canadian Popular Culture and the American Other -- tCommunications and Cultural Penetration -- tAmerican Culture in a Changing World -- tAwakening from the National Broadcasting Dream: Rethinking Television Regulation for National Cultural Goals -- tBroadcasting and Canadian Culture: A Commentary -- tA Sweet Hope of Glory in My Soul: Television Evangelism in the United States and Canada -- tInflecting the Formula: The First Seasons of Street Legal and L.A. Law -- tAmerican Sports and Canadian Society -- tPopular Cultures of Olympic Sport in Canada and the United States -- tWhose National Pastime? Baseball in Canadian Popular Culture -- tAmbivalence at the Fifty-five-Yard Line: Transformation and Resistance in Canadian Football -- tStage, Screen, and Soundtrack -- tMounties, Muggings, and Moose: Canadian Icons in a Landscape of American Violence -- tSyncretizing Sound: The Emergence of Canadian Popular Music -- tOur House, Their House Canadian Cinema's Coming of Age -- tWives, Whores, and Priests: Gender Relations and Narrative Voices in Two Quebecois Traditions -- tMerchandising Culture -- tThe Canadianization of an American Fair: The Case of Expo 86 -- tCulture for Sale: American Dollars Preferred -- tReflections -- tMade in America: The Problem of Mass Culture in Canada -- tAmerican Popular Culture and the Canadian State: The Case of Pornography -- tAmerican Popular Culture in Canada: Trends and Reflections -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributing authors explore three aspects of American culture: its transmission by means of print and broadcast media and through live events in sport, entertainment, religious evangelism, and other public productions; its influence on Canadian popular culture; and the variety of Canadian responses. They suggest that the Canadian version of American popular culture is far more than a copy. Instead, it is frequently a creative response - often parodic in tone and subversive in intent - that gives public expression to Canadian sentiment and sensibility and provides protection from, and resistance to, American domination. Ironically, it may be in responding to American culture that Canadian sovereignty finds its most meaningful and potent articulation. Specialists and scholars from a wide variety of disciplines, the contributors discuss a range of cultural forms and performances. Each example, while "made in Canada," is related to an American alternative but has a large Canadian audience. Taking a rich variety of perspectives on this complex relationship, The Beaver Bites Back? demands that Canadian popular culture be accorded its proper status. The contributors are G. Stuart Adam, Michael M. Ames, Robert Knight Barney, Seth Feldman, Bruce Feldhusen, David H. Flaherty, Reid Gilbert, Andrew Lyons, Harriet Lyons, John MacAloon, Frank E. Manning, Thelma McCormack, Mary Jane Miller, Bernard Ostry, Charline Poirier, Paul Rutherford, Robert A. Stebbins, Michael Taft, Geoffrey Wall, and Andrew Wernick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  